<dl id="n08070h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08070h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08070h"> 70(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Thou (foul abuse) / then you</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Thou</i> &hellip; for some time was reserved for religious and literary use as well as for foul abuse, until finally &hellip; <i>you</i> became the only form used in ordinary conversation. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 232</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02227e" href="c2all.htm#c02227e">VI.C.02:227(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
